Project #2: Polio in Modern Times

Hello, all readers! My name is Daniel Miller. I am a freshman at Pennsylvania State University, studying applied data science. This is my first exploratory data analysis project, and I have chosen to analyze something that has always fascinated me. Going into this project, I initially had a few different subjects on my mind. First, I had it in my head that I would explore some data on weather and climate, possibly to see if the conclusions made regarding climate change were as serious as the news claimed. However, with further thought, I have decided that it would be more interesting to delve into an infectious disease. In particular, some of the infectious diseases that once plagued the world amassed hundreds of thousands of cases as the developing world took shape in the 19th and 20th centuries. Unfortunately, the data on viruses such as smallpox and the Spanish flu was not easy to come across, and making any conclusions would all be a retrospective analysis.

Therefore, I decided to choose a disease that was once a very infectious disease but has not been eradicated, like smallpox. When speaking with my parents, who had grown up during the 1980's, they mentioned that a large-scale virus amongst families in the United States of America was the spread of polio.

The polio virus, scientifically referred to as poliomyelitis, was feared by parents across the globe as it occurred primarily in children ages 5 or under. It would initially appear as a cold, with fever, fatigue, and headache as the initial symptoms. However, it could lead to permanent paralysis. In particular, paralysis in the lower extremities and possibly even death if the paralysis takes form in the neck. Famously, President Franklin Delanor Roosevelt suffered greatly from the disease beginning at age 39, although it is quite uncommon for the virus to affect someone of that age.

As this is such an old virus, I think that it is important to study how polio terrorized the world. Aside from the origin of the virus, it is important in the field of data science to learn how it continues to affect people in more modern times, to learn from the past, and to prepare for what is to come of Polio and the newer virus' to improve future prevention measures. In the realm of biological warfare, a virus like polio could cripple the human race, and understanding how to fight disease is just as important as creating the cure.

Data Gathering

In looking for an open source database, I first looked through all of the government database websites and then turned my attention to some user-based websites, with no luck. However, when I searched through the CDC's databases, I found two that seemed particularly interesting. In the first, the number of reported polio cases in the majority of countries across the world from 19802020. Although I tried to find data on the cases before 1980, I had no luck in finding such a dataset. The second dataset I found illustrates the percentage of the U.S. population that has received the vaccine between 1962 and 2009. In my search, this was the largest range of years that I could find with a reliable dataset. I obtained the data for the first dataset from the Global Change Data Lab through their online publication at the link: https://ourworldindata.org/polio#all-charts. If you scroll to the bottom of the page, it can be downloaded in the second chart once selected.

Question 3, What trends emerge when plotting the data?

Now I will employ Matplotlib and Pandas to generate a plot of the data. By plotting the data, I would like to see if there is anything interesting that the change in format shows within the dataset.

Question 6, What countries have had the largest change in cases from the beginning of the dataset to the end of the dataset?

To answer this, I will generate the difference between the first 5 years of data and the final five years of data to see which countries have to conclude which countries have reduced the number of cases the most.

I will generate the difference column using a simple subtraction between the two columns I generated titled "1980-1984" and "2016-2020." This is done by using df['new_column'] = df['col1'] - df['col2'] as shown in the code below. I then employed the df.sort_values() function as done prior to creating a new data frame with only the top 10 in the difference. However, this time I sorted in ascending order, as the negative values indicate a decrease in the number of cases.

df['difference_firstlast5'] = df['2016-2020']-df['1980-1984']

Answer to Question 6:

Over the past 40 years, India has decreased the frequency of cases of polio the most, with 900,000 fewer cases in 2016-2020 than in 1980-1984 at the beginning of the dataset. Question 7, How did Covid-19 impact the number of cases on the world?

Now we will look at the final couple years of the dataset, when COVID-19 hit the world. In[92]:

Answer to Question 9:

I have reason to believe that the number of cases reported before the rapid increase in vaccinated population from mandates is misreported, as there was a sudden dropoff of roughly 50 cases per year down to 0, and there is no obvious reason for this shift. Although the vaccine was released to the public during the 1960's, only about half received it, making the sudden drop in cases highly unlikely. As the CDC did not track the progress of the vaccine to the public during the years of 1986-1990, it is likely that they also neglected to count the number of cases for budgeting reasons. However, it is also possible that it was misreported to aid the marketing of the vaccine, although this is simply speculation.

Question 10, Why did the tracking of vaccine distribution in the U.S. took a sudden halt in the late 1980's?

Answer to Question 10:

All of the vaccines that were tracked back in the 1980s did not report the data for the years 19861990. Doing some outside research, those were years of economic turmoil for the U.S., as funding for the CDC was likely removed or deemed unnecessary. Furthermore, in the early 1990s, initiatives were made to mandate specific vaccines for children, and the polio 3+ vaccine was among those mandated. This can be seen in the CDC article at the link: https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00039897.htm. However, the campaigning for children to receive vaccines was already in progress prior to the official mandate. Therefore, I would conclude that the lack of tracking the population who received the vaccine was not individual to the polio 3+ vaccine.

Throughout the execution of this project, I have learned how to utilize Matplotlib and Pandas to analyze a dataset. Although the scope of this project is effectively retrospective, it focuses on a virus that is becoming more dormant as the world develops. This makes the essence of this project exploratory. Although I am not aware of how to use a data frame to statistically prove any of my theories without doubt, making inferences off of generated tables and graphs got me to think that doing research on large-scale data is something that I would like to continue to do in my professional career. The majority of my thinking process came from looking at notable places in the dataset, noticably the beginning and end of the data, and then calculating sums and plotting the data to see if anything stood out to me. One thing that I found particularly interesting was the sudden increase in paralytic poliomyelitis before the COVID-19 pandemic, signifying a change after an all-time low. This signifies an importance of studying the spread of older diseases, as mutations can occur that would pose a threat on the current vaccines. Furthermore, there is nothing that I was able to find through some basic research that would account for a sudden drop in case tracking in 2016, although it is entirely possible that some form of error was involved. Overall, performing this project alone taught me more than just time management; putting time and energy into the project was far more important. As soon as I was interested in learning more about how such a life-altering disease put fear into people across the globe, I continuously wanted to learn more. Although I still have much more to learn, I am grateful for the experience and motivation to complete an exploratory data analysis, given the resources we have been taught over the past few weeks.
